Brazilian Senate Parties and Bolsonaroâ€™s Political Agenda (2019-2020)

TADA Final Project Report

Ana Benevides, Carol Sobral, Stefania Molina

2020-12-21

Abstract

In this study, we examine the collection of speeches made in the Brazilian Senate in the period of 2019-2020 to assess how three dimensions of Bolsonaroâ€™s political agenda resonate within the discussions being held in the Senate House. We start by exploring the composition of the Brazilian Senate, in terms of party, state of origin, and gender. Turning to scaling, we compare party ideologies in the Right-Left scale based on Senateâ€™s speeches with an assessment made by the Brazilian press. Then we estimate party positions using the manifestos from the 2018 presidential elections.Finally, in assessing the three dimensions of Bolsonaroâ€™s agenda, we conclude that economic discussions seem more polarized, with a distinct preference for certain words and topics, depending on RILE position. Discussions based on security and gender & family are less prevalent in the corpus and do not suggest a strong differentiation in the vocabulary employed.

Introduction

With the support of a Party coalition named â€œBrazil above everything, God above everyoneâ€, Bolsonaro was elected, in 2018, president of Brazil for the 2019-2022 term. Having served as congress representative (â€œdeputado federalâ€) for the State of Rio de Janeiro since 1991, Bolsonaro reached notoriety for his populist and often sexist, homophobic, anti-human rights, and anti-democratic political views.

After 4 consecutive elections of a left party (â€œLabour Partyâ€, i.e.Â â€œPartido do Trabalhadoresâ€ â€“ PT) for the presidency of Brazil, and in the aftermath of a controversial conviction of its most prominent leader â€“ and front runner in the election polls â€“ on corruption charges1, Bolsonaro benefited from a rise in anti-left sentiment and took the leadership of the poll with a manifesto that was filled with religious/Christian language and that was based on three pillars, that were directly opposed to the agenda of left/progressive groups:

  1. Liberalization of economic policy: promising deregulation, privatization, and extinction of sectors of the public service;

  2. Public security policy: a criminal reform package meant to harden convictions for crimes; exempt law enforcement officials of liability for any deaths they may cause in service; facilitate the private possession of firearms;

  3. Conservative moral agenda: opposition of sex education in schools; opposition to policies that aim at extending equality of rights for LGBT people; opposition to pregnancy termination, even in the limited circumstances allowed in Brazilian Law (rape; health risk for the woman; anencephaly of the fetus); reinforcement of gender stereotypical roles.

For this project, we assess if, and to what extent, these three axes that constitute Bolsonaroâ€™s political agenda are also resonating in the Brazilian Senate.

Brazilâ€™s Senate House is composed of 3 senators per state and the Federal District, totaling 81 senators. Each term in office lasts for 8 years, but the election cycle happens every 4 years, alternating the elections for 2/3 and 1/3 of the house. Theoretically speaking, the alternate election cycle should render the Senate House less sensitive to momentary waves that, if salient in a given moment, could heavily influence the course of a presidential election.

In 2018, 2/3 of the Senate chairs were elected (54 senators), while the remaining 1/3 had still half the term in office to complete.

In this project, we analyzed the corpus of senatorsâ€™ speeches from 2019-2020, focusing on issues associated with these salient dimensions of Bolsonaroâ€™s political plan.

Data

Letâ€™s start by briefly describing the data we will use in our analysis. The preliminary steps we took to assemble this information, can in found in our initial codes on the GitHub page for this project. The two data frames containing Senate information were downloaded through the Brazilian Senate API.

  • sen_df: a data frame containing information on senators (name, gender, term in office, party affiliation, state, etc.).
  • speech_df: a data frame containing all speeches from Brazilian senators for the period of 2019-2020.
  • cemf_2019: a data frame containing a Brazilian press assessment of partiesâ€™ positions in 2019.2
  • pres_df: a data frame containing all manifestos from Brazilâ€™s Presidential Election of 2018.

Senate

General Characteristics

Considering that the 26 states plus the Federal District each are entitled to three senators, we would expect sen_df to have 81 senators, however, Roraima (RR) had one of its senators (Chico Rodrigues)3 suspended from his activities following an investigation on diversion of resources. For this analysis, we will consider the Federal District a state.

The Senate API only displays current senatorsâ€™ speeches, which is why Roraima only has 2 senators and the corpus only comprises speeches from 80 senators.

In what concerns gender, although females are the majority of the Brazilian population (97 males per 100 females)4, women represent only 1/8 of the composition of the Senate House. 18 states have only male senators (including Roraima, with only 2 senators); 8 states have 2 male senators and 1 female senator and 1 state has 2 female senators and 1 male senator (Mato Grosso do Sul - MS)

In terms of party distribution, 16 parties have at least one senator in the present term. MDB, PSD, and PODEMOS are the parties with the largest representation, holding 13, 12, and 10 senators, respectively. All of PSD senators are male, while MDB and PODEMOS have 1 female senator each. Looking into the distribution of gender per party, 9 of these parties have at least one female senator; but only 1 party (PP) has 2 female senators.

Considering these characteristics of the Senate House, letâ€™s see if the speech distribution follows the same pattern, i.e., letâ€™s check if femalesâ€™ are responsible for 1/8 of the total speeches, and how speeches are distributed among these 16 parties, and among the 27 states.

Gender

We see that women represent 12.5% of the Senate but are responsible for only 8.79% of the speeches. This result seems consistent with indicators for gender inequality in Brazil and their effects on women in the workplace.

# Expected frequency of speeches per gender -- based on the number of  senators
expected <-  sen_df %>% 
  group_by(gender) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  mutate(prop = (n / sum(n))*100) %>% 
  rename(n_sen = n, prop_sen = prop, Gender = gender)

# Observed frequency of speeches
observed <- speech_df  %>% 
  group_by(Gender) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  mutate(prop = (n / sum(n))*100) %>% 
  rename(n_speech = n, prop_speech = prop)

merge(expected, observed, by = 'Gender') %>% 
  select(Gender, prop_sen, prop_speech) %>% 
  pivot_longer(!Gender, names_to = 'Proportion', values_to = 'Value') %>% 
  mutate(across(is.numeric, ~ round(., 2))) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Value, Proportion, group = Gender, fill = Gender)) +
  geom_col(position = 'dodge') + 
  geom_text(aes(label = Value), position = position_dodge(0.9), 
            show.legend = FALSE, vjust = -0.5) +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal()

One final thing needs to be mentioned about Brazilian politics current state of affairs. In recent years, politicians in Brazil have often changed parties. This happens mostly out of ideological differences and conflicts with party leadership. In fact, Bolsonaro has been partyless (â€˜S/ Partidoâ€™) for over a year.

The lack of party loyalty and identification that is currently a trend in the Brazilian political context might render any study that attempts to draw an inference about party positions from politiciansâ€™ speeches susceptible to criticism. Katia Abreu, for instance, has been associated with 3 different parties in the period of 2019-2020, and has also been partyless for a while. In order to assess the degree to which this study is vulnerable to this criticism, we listed bellow the changes in party affiliation that affect our corpus.

Overall, 17 senators (23%) have changed party affiliation at least once in the period of analysis. These shifts in affiliation explain why speech_df contains 22 parties, as it lists senatorsâ€™ parties according to affiliation at the time of the speech. sen_df only contains 16 parties, as it displays senatorsâ€™ affiliations as they stand today.

States

Our data set is composed of 5188 speeches given by 80 senators from 27 states. Assuming each senator uses speaking opportunities equally, we would expect each state to have around 192 speeches. What we see is that senators coming from some states, such as RS, PE, DF, and AP far exceed the expected average of speeches; at the same time, senators from PB, AC, and RJ seem not to have spoken as much as their peers in 2019 and 2020.

This might indicate that the items relevant for the agenda of the states that have more speeches might bear higher weight in the corpus.

Speeches Scaling

First, we use Wordfish as the text scaling method for the Senate speeches. After, as shown below, we plot the results of a fitted scaling model. The plot shows PL as the party farthest to the right and PT as the one farthest to the left.

# Main Senate Corpus

                   text_field = 'Pronunciamento')

# Main Senate DFM

  tolower = TRUE,
  remove_punct = TRUE,
  remove = stopwords('portuguese'),
  remove_numbers = TRUE,
  remove_separators = TRUE,
  remove_symbols = TRUE,
  stem = FALSE,

docnames(dfmat_sen) <- paste(dfmat_sen$Partido)

# Wordfish
wf <- textmodel_wordfish(dfmat_sen, dir = c(16, 6), sparse = TRUE) # PT and PL
textplot_scale1d(wf)

Wordfish Scores X Media

To better understand the Senate speeches positions generated with Wordfish, we compare them with the media perception of each party.

Wordfish vs Media assessment

The graph below shows a press assessment - Congresso em Foco - (y-axis) and the Wordfish categorization (x-axis) for each party.

Some parties appear in similar positions in both situations, such as PSB, PSDB, and MDB. On the other hand, the Wordfish model considers PT to be in the extreme left, around -2 on the scale. In contrast, the media categorization considers the same party in the left, at -1 on the scale.

We see the same pattern on the other side of the scale. While the media puts PSL in the right, the Wordfish model assumes the same party is located in the center.

# Code right, left, center positions 
cemf_2019 <-  cemf_2019 %>%

2018â€™s Presidential Manifestos

In this section, we use Austin to estimate party positions from presidential manifestos for the 2018 election.

# Corpus presidential speeches
corp_pres <- corpus(pres_df, docid_field = 'party', 
                   text_field = 'text')

# DFM 
dfmat_pres <- dfm(corp_pres,
  tolower = TRUE,
  remove_punct = TRUE,
  remove = stopwords('portuguese'),
  remove_numbers = TRUE,
  remove_separators = TRUE,
  remove_symbols = TRUE,
  stem = FALSE)

dfmat_pres <- dfm_select(dfmat_pres, min_nchar = 2)

Austin Prediction

The graph illustrates party positions derived with Austin from the presidential manifestos (y-axis) and positions for Senate speeches (x-axis) derived from an out-of-sample prediction. Parties have more extreme positions based on presidential manifestos. This might suggest that when running presidential elections, parties adopt in their manifestos more clear-cut positions, as they are catering to their preferred constituency. In everyday discussions in the Senate, however, positions seem to be more fluid, and less extreme - something also evidenced by the aforementioned lack of party loyalty/identification coming from at least 23% of the senators.

# Austin
# Convert to WFM
wfm_pres <- as.wfm(dfmat_pres, word.margin = 2)

# Wordfish pres
wfa_pres <- wordfish(wfm_pres, dir = c(4, 3)) # PSOL, PSL

# pres scores
theta_pres_au <- as.data.frame(wfa_pres$theta, wfa_pres$docs) %>%
  rownames_to_column('party') %>%
  rename(theta_pres = 'wfa_pres$theta')

# Match sen features with pres
dfmat_sen_match <- dfm_match(dfmat_sen, featnames(dfmat_pres))

# Convert to WFM
wfm_sen <- as.wfm(dfmat_sen_match, word.margin = 2)

# Out of sample Austin prediction to senate speeches
theta_sen_au <- as.data.frame(predict(wfa_pres, newdata = wfm_sen)) %>%
  rownames_to_column('party') %>%
  rename(theta_sen_au = 'predict(wfa_pres, newdata = wfm_sen)')

# merge dfs -- theta pres and sen
theta_ps <- merge(theta_pres_au, theta_sen_au, by = 'party')

# Compare pres x sen
theta_ps %>% 
  arrange(theta_pres) %>%    
  mutate(party = factor(party, levels = party)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = theta_pres, y = theta_sen_au, label = party, col = party)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_label_repel(show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_abline(linetype = 'dotted') +
  xlim(-2, 2) +
  ylim(-2, 2) +
  ylab('Predicted Position for Senate Corpus') +
  xlab('Position from Presidential Corpus') +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = 'none')

Themes

Having assessed how the parties in the Senate are positioned in the RILE scale, letâ€™s check how the discussions on the three topics of Bolsonaroâ€™s agenda appear in the Senate.

For this section, we employed a dictionary analysis, identifying a few words with each topic to classify the corpus accordingly.

We initially consulted the â€œLexiCoder Policy Agendaâ€ dictionary to have a baseline for words that could capture these main topics. We then translated the words into Portuguese and adapted them for the Brazilian context.

In the following sections, we will analyze the three aforementioned dimensions under the topics Economy, Security, and Gender & Family.

To extract documents for each topic, we filtered texts that have higher scores in a determined topic when compared to the others.

# Create Dictionary with themes of interest

RILE Features

The graph displays words that push a document farthest to the left or the right. Words located at the bottom are used less frequently. Right and left word positions (beta) range from approximately -2.5 to 2.

The words that most contributed for a left-leaning document are petrobrÃ¡s (an oil extracting public company whose privatization is a contentious topic), anticapitalista (â€˜anticapitalistâ€™), cut (â€˜centralized labour unionâ€™), auxÃ­lio-doenÃ§a (â€˜illness aidâ€™, an employment benefit), sindicalista (â€˜unionistâ€™) and terceirizaÃ§Ã£o (â€˜outsourcingâ€™).

For the right, the words are militarismo (â€˜militarismâ€™), agroindustriais (â€˜agribusinessâ€™), grevista (â€˜strikerâ€™), veterinÃ¡ria (â€˜veterinarianâ€™), logÃ­stica (â€˜logisticsâ€™) and transportes (â€˜transportâ€™).

In general, the right discusses business, agriculture, and themes related to a somewhat liberal agenda (with words like entrepreneurship, liberalism, and infrastructure). The left discusses pension benefits, workerâ€™s rights, and trade unionism.

Both sides talk about macroeconomic policies, with words like inflation, GDP, debt, and spending.

RILE Features

The graph displays words that push a document farthest to the left or the right. Words located at the bottom are used less frequently. Right and left word positions range from approximately -1.5 to 2.0.

The words that most contributed for a left-leaning document are defensoria (â€˜public attorney officeâ€™), defensores (either â€˜public attorneysâ€™, or â€˜defendersâ€™), direitos (â€˜rightsâ€™), humanos (â€˜humanâ€™), perseguiÃ§Ã£o (â€˜harassmentâ€™), liberdade (â€˜freedomâ€™) . For the right, the words are vagabundo(s) (â€˜trampsâ€™), juvenis (â€˜juvenileâ€™), tropa (â€˜troopâ€™), pcc (the largest gang in SP) and feminicÃ­dio (â€˜feminicideâ€™).

In general, the right discusses crime, criminals, and law enforcement activities, while the left discusses human rights and judicial harassment.

Interestingly, the use of cadeia (â€˜jailâ€™) and prisÃ£o (â€˜prisonâ€™), which are synonyms in Portuguese, seems associated with speeches on different sides of the RILE spectrum. Similarly, the word vagabundagem (idleness that characterizes a tramp) and vagabundo(s) (â€˜trampâ€™) are also associated with different sides of RILE.

Finally, feminicÃ­dio (a relatively new criminal offense for an aggravated homicide committed against a woman by her former romantic partner), which is a differentiation to standard homicide typically criticized by right-wing politicians with a conservative view of gender issues, is the word that appears most strongly associated with a right-leaning political view.

Conclusion

From our analysis, we infer that not all themes present in Bolsonaroâ€™s discourse have the same relevance in the speeches of the Brazilian Senate.

Economy bears a higher weight in the discussions in the Senate, and better reflects the partisan division between those on the left that advocate for a heterodox approach, with state driving investment, and those on the right, that tend to favor an orthodox approach, advocating for liberal policies. Security and Gender & Family seem less salient in the discussions of the Senate, and there seems to be a bigger overlap in the use of vocabulary by parties from different sides of the spectrum.

While Bolsonaroâ€™s agenda is certainly contentious in Brazilian society, making for daily headlines in the Brazilian press, the Senate doesnâ€™t seem to give the same weight to discussing his proposals for Security and Gender & Family as we would have expected just from reading the newspapers.

On the other hand, a prevalence of speeches from the opposition may explain, at least in part, the lack of resonance of Bolsonaroâ€™s project in the Senate. Take PT as an example; it is one of the main opposition parties to Bolsonaro and has a large participation in overall Senate speeches.
